1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,000
In this short video, we will get an overview of managing our media settings.

2
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:08,000
If you visit the Media Library, you are able to view and filter through all your media items.

3
00:00:11,000 --> 00:00:14,000
But do you know how WordPress stores images?

4
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:17,000
Well, to get a deep understanding of that, we need to make our way to "Settings" and then click on "Media".

5
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:25,000
WordPress automatically generates three sizes when you upload an image, thumbnail, medium and large.

6
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:33,000
But you might be asking, "Why?"

7
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:35,000
If you upload a large image, WordPress resizes it to fit these categories to improve site speed.

8
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:42,000
Some themes can instruct WordPress on which image size to use in various locations,

9
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:47,000
such as featured images on posts or thumbnails in a blog listing.

10
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:52,000
You will notice that when I add an image to a page, the large size is added by default,

11
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:58,000
as it is a reduced file size compared to the original image I added.

12
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:02,000
When it comes to selecting the right resolution size for your images,

13
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:06,000
it's important to consider the intended size of the image on your website.

14
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:11,000
For example, if you have a photo that you want to use as a banner at the top of your website,

15
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:16,000
using the medium or thumbnail resolution would result in a pixelated appearance.

16
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:22,000
In contrast, thumbnail sizes are more suitable for small preview images in lists or widgets,

17
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:28,000
while medium sizes can be used alongside other elements on a page or post.

18
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:33,000
It is advised to optimize images before uploading them to your Media Library

19
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:38,000
or using an optimization plugin to achieve maximum optimization.

20
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:43,000
Check out our video about image optimization to gain a better understanding.

21
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:48,000
You can update the width and the height of image sizes,

22
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:52,000
but I would suggest leaving the default settings as is.

23
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:56,000
The last option under media settings allows you to choose how media will be filed

24
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:01,000
in your site's uploads folder in the back end.

25
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:04,000
WordPress will, by default, save your media in folders according to month and year.

26
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:09,000
And if you deselect this option, all images may end up in one folder.

